# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: convex-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Convexity implies certain global features of a problem.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] For example, in a convex optimization problem, every local minimum is also a global minimum.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Convex sets can often be separated by hyperplanes, and convex functions can be studied through supporting affine functions.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Convex analysis is a common thread in modern optimization, duality theory, and the study of nonsmooth problems.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] The tools of convex analysis include the epigraph of a function, the subdifferential, the Legendre–Fenchel transform, and the Fenchel–Moreau theorem.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] These allow many constrained problems to be rewritten in geometric form and many optimization problems to be paired with dual problems.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] The simplest convex subsets of Euclidean space are points, line segments, affine subspaces, half-spaces, balls, cones, and convex polytopes.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Intersections of convex sets are convex, so many complicated convex sets can be described as intersections of simpler ones.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] For example, a polyhedron in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is the intersection of finitely many half-spaces.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Examples of convex functions include affine functions, quadratic functions (with positive semidefinite Hessian), norms, and the maximum of a family of affine functions.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Convex analysis also uses extended real-valued functions, which may take the value $+\infty$ .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] This convention allows constraints to be incorporated directly into a function.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Minimizing f over C is then the same as minimizing $f+\iota _{C}$ over the whole space.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] This means that the line segment between x and y lies entirely in C .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] for all $x,y\in C$ and all $0\leq t\leq 1$ .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] It is strictly convex if the inequality is strict whenever $x\neq y$ and $0<t<1$ , apart from degenerate cases where the two sides are forced to be equal.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] The epigraph is the region lying on or above the graph of the function.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] This observation is one reason convex functions and convex sets are studied together: statements about convex functions can often be translated into statements about convex sets in one higher dimension.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] A function is called proper if its effective domain is nonempty and it never takes the value $-\infty$ .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Proper convex functions are the usual objects of study in convex analysis.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Convex analysis takes different forms in finite-dimensional and infinite-dimensional spaces.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] In finite-dimensional Euclidean space, many geometric and topological complications are absent: all norms are equivalent, every linear functional is continuous, and closed and bounded sets are compact.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] As a result, many results can be stated using ordinary Euclidean topology.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] For example, a continuous convex function on a closed bounded convex subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ attains its minimum, and separation theorems can often be formulated in elementary geometric terms.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] In infinite-dimensional spaces, the topology of the underlying vector space becomes part of the theory.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] The relevant dual space is usually the continuous dual space, and many statements depend on whether one uses the norm topology, a weak topology, or another locally convex topology.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Closed and bounded sets need not be compact, linear functionals may fail to be continuous unless continuity is assumed, and convex sets that are large in an algebraic sense may have empty interior in the norm topology.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] In finite dimensions, coercivity or compactness hypotheses often ensure the existence of minimizers.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] In infinite-dimensional spaces, minimizing sequences may fail to have convergent subsequences in the norm topology.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Existence results therefore often use weak compactness, lower semicontinuity, and reflexivity assumptions, such as those in the direct methods in the calculus of variations.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] For example, in a reflexive Banach space, closed bounded convex sets have useful weak compactness properties, making weak lower semicontinuity a standard tool in variational problems.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Interior-point conditions also become more delicate in infinite dimensions.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] In finite-dimensional convex optimization, conditions such as Slater's condition are often expressed using the ordinary interior or relative interior of a convex set.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] In infinite-dimensional spaces, many natural convex sets have empty interior, so alternative notions such as algebraic interior, core, quasi-relative interior, or other constraint qualifications may be used.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] The Fenchel–Moreau theorem and related duality theorems require appropriate lower semicontinuity and convexity hypotheses relative to the chosen topology.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Thus is closely tied to functional analysis, locally convex spaces, Banach spaces, Hilbert spaces, and monotone operator theory.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Convex analysis allows many problems to be formulated both in terms of the original vector space and its dual space.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] For example, a convex set can be described both in terms of its set of points and the set of hyperplanes that meet it.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] A non-empty closed convex set can also be described by its set of supporting hyperplanes.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] For convex functions, duality also plays an important role.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Geometrically, the convex conjugate describes the supporting affine functions of the epigraph of f .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] If this hyperplane touches the epigraph at $(x,f(x))$ , then it is a supporting hyperplane there.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] or equivalently $x^{*}\in \partial f(x)$ , the subdifferential of f at x .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Many problems in convex analysis have a corresponding dual problem.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] In general, the dual problem is formulated on a dual vector space and gives bounds on the value of the original, or *primal*, problem.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Under additional hypotheses these bounds are exact, a property known as strong duality.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] A simple geometric example is the relation between a norm and its dual norm.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Thus the unit ball of a norm and the unit ball of the dual norm determine one another by polar duality.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Under suitable closedness hypotheses, the bipolar theorem says that C can be recovered from its polar by taking the polar again.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] A central analytic example is Fenchel duality.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Let $A:X\to Y$ be a continuous linear map between locally convex spaces, and let $f:X\to (-\infty ,+\infty ]$ and $g:Y\to (-\infty ,+\infty ]$ be proper convex functions.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Under standard regularity or constraint qualification assumptions, equality holds.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] The usual Lagrange duality of constrained optimization is a special case of this general principle.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Every feasible choice of the multiplier vector $\lambda$ gives a lower bound on the primal minimum.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] When a condition such as Slater's condition holds, the optimal dual value equals the optimal primal value for many finite-dimensional convex programs.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] The dual variables y may be interpreted as the multipliers attached to the equality constraints $Ax=b$ .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Duality is especially useful for *certifying* solutions to optimization problems.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] If a feasible primal point and a feasible dual point have the same objective value, then both are optimal.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] In this way, convex duality converts an optimization problem into a pair of mutually checking problems, one in the original space and one in the dual space.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] A general way to construct dual problems in convex analysis uses a perturbation function.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] The convex conjugate of F is defined on $X^{*}\times Y^{*}$ .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] When equality holds, the primal and dual problems are said to satisfy strong duality.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Conditions ensuring equality are usually stated as regularity or constraint-qualification hypotheses, such as interior-point conditions in finite-dimensional convex optimization.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] This perturbation framework includes many familiar dualities as special cases, including Fenchel duality and Lagrange duality.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Different choices of the perturbation function F can lead to different dual problems for the same primal optimization problem.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Convex functions need not be differentiable.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] For example, the absolute value function $f(x)=|x|$ is convex but is not differentiable at $x=0$ .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Convex analysis therefore uses a generalized derivative called a subgradient.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Let $f:X\to (-\infty ,+\infty ]$ be a convex function on a real vector space, and let $X^{*}$ be a suitable dual space.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] The set of all subgradients at x is the subdifferential of f at x , denoted $\partial f(x)$ .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Geometrically, a subgradient defines a supporting hyperplane to the epigraph of f .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] If f is differentiable at x , then the subdifferential consists of the ordinary derivative.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Subgradients give a basic optimality condition.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] This generalizes the familiar condition $\nabla f(x)=0$ for differentiable functions.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Convex analysis often studies functions that are lower semi-continuous rather than continuous.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] A function $f:X\to (-\infty ,+\infty ]$ is lower semicontinuous if, roughly speaking, its values cannot suddenly jump downward.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Thus lower semicontinuous convex functions are often called closed convex functions.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Lower semicontinuity is important in optimization because it helps ensure that minimizing limits do not lose the value of the function.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] This condition is weaker than continuity, but it is often strong enough for existence theorems, especially when combined with compactness or weak compactness assumptions.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] The convex conjugate of any function is convex and lower semicontinuous with respect to the appropriate weak-* topology.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] The conjugate of the conjugate, or biconjugate, gives the closed convex envelope of the original function.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] if and only if f is convex and lower semicontinuous.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Equivalently, closed proper convex functions are exactly the functions that can be recovered from their affine minorants.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] In convex optimization, the objective is to minimize a convex function over a convex set.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Convexity ensures that every local minimum is a global minimum, and duality often provides certificates of optimality.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Linear programming, quadratic programming, semidefinite programming, and many methods in statistics and machine learning use this framework.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Convex analysis is also connected with convex geometry, which studies convex bodies, polytopes, supporting hyperplanes, mixed volumes, and related geometric inequalities.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Classical finite-dimensional results such as Carathéodory's theorem (convex hull), Helly's theorem, and Radon's theorem describe the combinatorial and geometric structure of convex hulls.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] These theorems are usually regarded as part of convex geometry, but they provide much of the geometric background for convex analysis.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] In functional analysis, compact convex sets are studied through their extreme points.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] The Krein–Milman theorem states that, under suitable hypotheses, a compact convex set in a locally convex space is generated by its extreme points.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Choquet theory refines this idea by representing points of compact convex sets as barycenters of probability measures supported on extreme points.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] This can be viewed as an infinite-dimensional analogue of writing a point of a polytope as a convex combination of its vertices.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Convexity is also used in probability theory.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Jensen's inequality compares the value of a convex function at an average with the average of its values.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Convex order compares probability measures by testing them against convex functions, and large deviations theory uses the Legendre–Fenchel transform to express rate functions as convex conjugates of logarithmic moment generating functions.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] In optimal transport, the Kantorovich formulation of the transport problem is a convex optimization problem over probability measures, and Kantorovich duality is a form of convex duality.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] For the quadratic cost on Euclidean space, Brenier's theorem relates optimal transport maps to gradients of convex functions, connecting optimal transport with the Monge–Ampère equation.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] Several areas use modified notions of convexity adapted to different structures.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] In the calculus of variations, rank-one convexity, polyconvexity, and quasiconvexity arise in vector-valued variational problems.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] In metric geometry and optimization on manifolds, geodesic convexity replaces line segments by geodesics.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-analysis] In several complex variables, notions such as pseudoconvexity, holomorphic convexity, polynomial convexity, and plurisubharmonic functions play roles analogous in some respects to convexity in real analysis.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] In mathematics and mathematical optimization, the **convex conjugate** of a function is a generalization of the Legendre transformation which applies to non-convex functions.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] It is also known as **Legendre–Fenchel transformation**, **Fenchel transformation**, or **Fenchel conjugate** (after Adrien-Marie Legendre and Werner Fenchel).
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] The convex conjugate is widely used for constructing the dual problem in optimization theory, thus generalizing Lagrangian duality.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] Let X be a real topological vector space and let $X^{*}$ be the dual space to X .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] This definition can be interpreted as an encoding of the convex hull of the function's epigraph in terms of its supporting hyperplanes.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] For more examples, see § Table of selected convex conjugates.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] The convex conjugate and Legendre transform of the exponential function agree except that the domain of the convex conjugate is strictly larger as the Legendre transform is only defined for positive real numbers.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] Let *F* denote a cumulative distribution function of a random variable *X*.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] A particular interpretation has the transform $f^{\text{inc}}(x):=\arg \sup _{t}t\cdot x-\int _{0}^{1}\max\{t-f(u),0\}\,du,$ as this is a nondecreasing rearrangement of the initial function *f*; in particular, $f^{\text{inc}}=f$ for *f* nondecreasing.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] The convex conjugate of a closed convex function is again a closed convex function.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] The convex conjugate of a polyhedral convex function (a convex function with polyhedral epigraph) is again a polyhedral convex function.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] The convex conjugate of a function is always lower semi-continuous.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] The Fenchel inequality (below) implies $f^{**}\leq f$ .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] More precisely, $f^{**}$ is the greatest lower semicontinuous convex function not exceeding f , often described as the closed convex envelope of f .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] In particular, by the Fenchel–Moreau theorem, a proper function is equal to its biconjugate if and only if it is convex and lower semicontinuous.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] Furthermore, the equality holds only when $p\in \partial f(x)$ , where $\partial f(x)$ is the subgradient.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] The ${*}$ operation is a convex mapping itself.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] The operation $\operatorname {\Box }$ is symmetric (commutative) and associative, i.e.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] which expresses the behaviour of convex conjugation with respect to sums of functions.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] The infimal convolution of two functions has a geometric interpretation: The (strict) epigraph of the infimal convolution of two functions is the Minkowski sum of the (strict) epigraphs of those functions.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] Let $A:X\to Y$ be a bounded linear operator.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-conjugate] The following table provides Legendre transforms for many common functions as well as a few useful properties.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] In mathematics, a real-valued function is called **convex** if the line segment between any two distinct points on the graph of the function lies above or on the graph of the function between the two points.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] Equivalently, a function is convex if its *epigraph* (the set of points on or above the graph of the function) is a convex set.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] In simple terms, a convex function graph is shaped like a cup $\cup$ (or a straight line like a linear function), while a concave function's graph is shaped like a cap $\cap$ .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] A twice-differentiable function of a single variable is convex if and only if its second derivative is nonnegative on its entire domain.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] Well-known examples of convex functions of a single variable include a linear function $f(x)=cx$ (where c is a real number), a quadratic function $cx^{2}$ ( c as a nonnegative real number) and an exponential function $ce^{x}$ ( c as a nonnegative real number).
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] Convex functions play an important role in many areas of mathematics.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] They are especially important in the study of optimization problems where they are distinguished by a number of convenient properties.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] For instance, a strictly convex function on an open set has no more than one minimum.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] Even in infinite-dimensional spaces, under suitable additional hypotheses, convex functions continue to satisfy such properties and as a result, they are the most well-understood functionals in the calculus of variations.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] In probability theory, a convex function applied to the expected value of a random variable is always bounded above by the expected value of the convex function of the random variable.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] This result, known as Jensen's inequality, can be used to deduce inequalities such as the arithmetic–geometric mean inequality and Hölder's inequality.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] Let X be a convex subset of a real vector space and let $f:X\to \mathbb {R}$ be a function.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] The sum $-\infty +\infty$ is also undefined so a convex extended real-valued function is typically only allowed to take exactly one of $-\infty$ and $+\infty$ as a value.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] A strictly convex function f is a function such that the straight line between any pair of points on the curve f is above the curve f except for the intersection points between the straight line and the curve.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] An example of a function which is convex but not strictly convex is $f(x,y)=x^{2}+y$ .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] This function is not strictly convex because any two points sharing an x coordinate will have a straight line between them, while any two points NOT sharing an x coordinate will have a greater value of the function than the points between them.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] The function f is said to be ***concave*** (resp.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] ***strictly concave***) if $-f$ ( f multiplied by −1) is convex (resp. strictly convex).
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] The term *convex* is often referred to as *convex down* or *concave upward*, and the term concave is often referred as *concave down* or *convex upward*.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] If the term "convex" is used without an "up" or "down" keyword, then it refers strictly to a cup shaped graph $\cup$ .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] As an example, Jensen's inequality refers to an inequality involving a convex or convex-(down), function.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] Many properties of convex functions have the same simple formulation for functions of many variables as for functions of one variable.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] See below the properties for the case of many variables, as some of them are not listed for functions of one variable.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] The concept of strong convexity extends and parametrizes the notion of strict convexity.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] Intuitively, a strongly-convex function is a function that grows as fast as a quadratic function.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] A strongly convex function is also strictly convex, but not vice versa.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] For example, let f be strictly convex, and suppose there is a sequence of points $(x_{n})$ such that $f''(x_{n})={\tfrac {1}{n}}$ .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] Even though $f''(x_{n})>0$ , the function is not strongly convex because $f''(x)$ will become arbitrarily small.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] Some authors, such as refer to functions satisfying this inequality as elliptic functions.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] It is not necessary for a function to be differentiable in order to be strongly convex.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] Notice that this definition approaches the definition for strict convexity as $m\to 0,$ and is identical to the definition of a convex function when $m=0.$ Despite this, functions exist that are strictly convex but are not strongly convex for any $m>0$ (see example below).
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] This is equivalent to requiring that the minimum eigenvalue of $\nabla ^{2}f(x)$ be at least m for all $x.$ If the domain is just the real line, then $\nabla ^{2}f(x)$ is just the second derivative $f''(x),$ so the condition becomes $f''(x)\geq m$ .
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] If $m=0$ then this means the Hessian is positive semidefinite (or if the domain is the real line, it means that $f''(x)\geq 0$ ), which implies the function is convex, and perhaps strictly convex, but not strongly convex.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] Assuming still that the function is twice continuously differentiable, one can show that the lower bound of $\nabla ^{2}f(x)$ implies that it is strongly convex.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] A function f is strongly convex with parameter *m* if and only if the function $x\mapsto f(x)-{\frac {m}{2}}\|x\|^{2}$ is convex.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] A twice continuously differentiable function f on a compact domain X that satisfies $f''(x)>0$ for all $x\in X$ is strongly convex.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] The proof of this statement follows from the extreme value theorem, which states that a continuous function on a compact set has a maximum and minimum.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] Strongly convex functions are in general easier to work with than convex or strictly convex functions, since they are a smaller class.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] Like strictly convex functions, strongly convex functions have unique minima on compact sets.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] A uniformly convex function, with modulus $\phi$ , is a function f that, for all $x,y$ in the domain and $t\in [0,1],$ satisfies $f(tx+(1-t)y)\leq tf(x)+(1-t)f(y)-t(1-t)\phi (\|x-y\|)$ where $\phi$ is a function that is non-negative and vanishes only at 0.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] This is a generalization of the concept of strongly convex function; by taking $\phi (\alpha )={\tfrac {m}{2}}\alpha ^{2}$ we recover the definition of strong convexity.
[src:convex-analysis/convex-function] It is worth noting that some authors require the modulus $\phi$ to be an increasing function, but this condition is not required by all authors.
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] Similarly, the **strict epigraph** $\operatorname {epi} _{S}f$ is the set of points in $X\times \mathbb {R}$ lying strictly above its graph.
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] Importantly, unlike the graph of $f,$ the epigraph *always* consists *entirely* of points in $X\times \mathbb {R}$ (this is true of the graph only when f is real-valued).
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] The study of continuous real-valued functions in real analysis has traditionally been closely associated with the study of their graphs, which are sets that provide geometric information (and intuition) about these functions.
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] Epigraphs serve this same purpose in the fields of convex analysis and variational analysis, in which the primary focus is on convex functions valued in $[-\infty ,\infty ]$ instead of continuous functions valued in a vector space (such as $\mathbb {R}$ or $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ ).
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] This is because in general, for such functions, geometric intuition is more readily obtained from a function's epigraph than from its graph.
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] Similarly to how graphs are used in real analysis, the epigraph can often be used to give geometrical interpretations of a convex function's properties, to help formulate or prove hypotheses, or to aid in constructing counterexamples.
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] In the union over $x\in f^{-1}(\mathbb {R} )$ that appears above on the right hand side of the last line, the set $\{x\}\times [f(x),\infty )$ may be interpreted as being a "vertical ray" consisting of $(x,f(x))$ and all points in $X\times \mathbb {R}$ "directly above" it.
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] Similarly, the set of points on or below the graph of a function is its hypograph.
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] This deficiency in $X\times [-\infty ,\infty ]$ remains even if instead of being a vector space, X is merely a non-empty subset of some vector space.
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] The epigraph being a subset of a vector space allows for tools related to real analysis and functional analysis (and other fields) to be more readily applied.
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] The domain (rather than the codomain) of the function is not particularly important for this definition; it can be any linear space or even an arbitrary set instead of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] The strict epigraph $\operatorname {epi} _{S}f$ and the graph $\operatorname {graph} f$ are always disjoint.
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] The epigraph of a function $f:X\to [-\infty ,\infty ]$ is related to its graph and strict epigraph by $\,\operatorname {epi} f\,\subseteq \,\operatorname {epi} _{S}f\,\cup \,\operatorname {graph} f$ where set equality holds if and only if f is real-valued.
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] However, $\operatorname {epi} f=\left[\operatorname {epi} _{S}f\,\cup \,\operatorname {graph} f\right]\,\cap \,[X\times \mathbb {R} ]$ always holds.
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] The epigraph is empty if and only if the function is identically equal to infinity.
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] Just as any function can be reconstructed from its graph, so too can any extended real-valued function f on X be reconstructed from its epigraph $E:=\operatorname {epi} f$ (even when f takes on $\pm \infty$ as a value).
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] A function is convex if and only if its epigraph is a convex set.
[src:convex-analysis/epigraph-mathematics] A function is lower semicontinuous if and only if its epigraph is closed.
[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] In mathematics, **Fenchel's duality theorem** is a result in the theory of convex functions named after Werner Fenchel.
[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] Let f be a proper convex function on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and let g be a proper concave function on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] where $f^{*}$ is the convex conjugate of f (also referred to as the Fenchel–Legendre transform) and $g_{*}$ is the concave conjugate of g .
[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] Let *X* and *Y* be Banach spaces, $f:X\to \mathbb {R} \cup \{+\infty \}$ and $g:Y\to \mathbb {R} \cup \{+\infty \}$ be convex functions and $A:X\to Y$ be a bounded linear map.
[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] Note that $f^{*}$ and $g^{*}$ are the convex conjugates of f and g , respectively, and $A^{*}$ is the adjoint operator.
[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] The perturbation function for this dual problem is given by $F(x,y)=f(x)+g(Ax-y)$ .
[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] 2. $A\operatorname {dom} f\cap \operatorname {cont} g\neq \emptyset$ where $\operatorname {cont}$ are the points where the function is continuous.
[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] If $d^{*}\in \mathbb {R}$ then supremum is attained.
