[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] One seeks to vary *x* such that the vertical distance between the convex and concave curves at *x* is as small as possible.
[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] The position of the vertical line in the figure is the (approximate) optimum.
[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] The next figure illustrates the maximization problem on the right hand side of the above equation.
[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] Tangents are drawn to each of the two curves such that both tangents have the same slope *p*.
[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] The problem is to adjust *p* in such a way that the two tangents are as far away from each other as possible (more precisely, such that the points where they intersect the y-axis are as far from each other as possible).
[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] Imagine the two tangents as metal bars with vertical springs between them that push them apart and against the two parabolas that are fixed in place.
[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] Fenchel's theorem states that the two problems have the same solution.
[src:convex-analysis/fenchel-s-duality-theorem] The points having the minimum vertical separation are also the tangency points for the maximally separated parallel tangents.
[src:convex-analysis/proximal-operator] For any function in this class, the minimizer of the right-hand side above is unique, hence making the proximal operator well-defined.
[src:convex-analysis/proximal-operator] The proximal operator is used in proximal gradient methods, which is frequently used in optimization algorithms associated with non-differentiable optimization problems such as total variation denoising.
[src:convex-analysis/proximal-operator] The ${\text{prox}}$ of a proper, lower semi-continuous convex function f enjoys several useful properties for optimization.
[src:convex-analysis/proximal-operator] showing that the proximity operator is indeed a generalisation of the projection operator.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] In mathematics, the **subderivative** (or **subgradient**) generalizes the derivative to convex functions which are not necessarily differentiable.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] The set of subderivatives at a point is called the **subdifferential** at that point.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] Subderivatives arise in convex analysis, the study of convex functions, often in connection to convex optimization.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] Let $f:I\to \mathbb {R}$ be a real-valued convex function defined on an open interval of the real line.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] Such a function need not be differentiable at all points: For example, the absolute value function $f(x)=|x|$ is non-differentiable when $x=0$ .
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] The slope of such a line is called a *subderivative*.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] Rigorously, a *subderivative* of a convex function $f:I\to \mathbb {R}$ at a point $x_{0}$ in the open interval I is a real number c such that $f(x)-f(x_{0})\geq c(x-x_{0})$ for all $x\in I$ .
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] If f is convex, then its subdifferential at any point is non-empty.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] Moreover, if its subdifferential at $x_{0}$ contains exactly one subderivative, then f is differentiable at $x_{0}$ and $\partial f(x_{0})=\{f'(x_{0})\}$ .
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] Consider the function $f(x)=|x|$ which is convex.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] Then, the subdifferential at the origin is the interval $[-1,1]$ .
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] The subdifferential at any point $x_{0}<0$ is the singleton set $\{-1\}$ , while the subdifferential at any point $x_{0}>0$ is the singleton set $\{1\}$ .
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] This is similar to the sign function, but is not single-valued at 0 , instead including all possible subderivatives.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] The concepts of subderivative and subdifferential can be generalized to functions of several variables.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] The set of all subgradients at $x_{0}$ is called the **subdifferential** at $x_{0}$ and is denoted $\partial f(x_{0})$ .
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] The subdifferential is always a nonempty convex compact set.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] These concepts generalize further to convex functions $f:U\to \mathbb {R}$ on a convex set in a locally convex space V .
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] The set of all subgradients at $x_{0}$ is called the subdifferential at $x_{0}$ and is again denoted $\partial f(x_{0})$ .
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] The subdifferential is always a convex closed set.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] It can be an empty set; consider for example an unbounded operator, which is convex, but has no subgradient.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] If f is continuous, the subdifferential is nonempty.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] For a proper convex function $f:X\to (-\infty ,+\infty ]$ on a locally convex space, the subdifferential can be characterized using the convex conjugate.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] The subdifferential on convex functions was introduced by Jean Jacques Moreau and R.
[src:convex-analysis/subderivative] The *generalized subdifferential* for nonconvex functions was introduced by Francis H.
